## Example 6 — Real-World: Simplify Scientific Notation Expression

A star is $4.2 \times 10^{13}$ km away. A probe travels at $3 \times 10^5$ km per year. How many years to reach the star?

### Step 1: Set Up the Division

$$\text{Time} = \frac{4.2 \times 10^{13}}{3 \times 10^5}$$

### Step 2: Divide the Coefficients

$$\frac{4.2}{3} = 1.4$$

### Step 3: Apply the Quotient Rule to the Powers of 10

$$\frac{10^{13}}{10^5} = 10^{13-5} = 10^8$$

### Step 4: Combine

$$\text{Time} = 1.4 \times 10^8 \text{ years}$$

### Step 5: Interpret

$1.4 \times 10^8 = 140{,}000{,}000$ years. This is 140 million years — far too long for a practical mission. This illustrates why interstellar travel is so challenging.

✅ Answer: $1.4 \times 10^8$ years (140 million years).

